muslim-hazara-community-people-are-protesting-against-killings)

People gather near the bodies of Hazara victims, who were gunned down by
unidentified armed men at the Scrap Market on Sarki Road in a targeted killing
in Quetta, Pakistan late last year. Image by PPPIimages. Copyright Demotix

Similarly, columnist [Mehr Tarar](https://twitter.com/MehrTarar) accused the
ruling party, [Pakistan People's
Party](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistan_Peoples_Party) (PPP), of doing
nothing to protect the Hazaras:

> [@MehrTarar](https://twitter.com/MehrTarar/status/302824299834785793):
> [#PPP](https://twitter.com/search?q=%23PPP&src=hash)-led govt was asked last
> month by the slain
> [#Hazaras](https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Hazaras&src=hash)‘ families to
> STOP (whatever that takes) the
> [#LeJ](https://twitter.com/search?q=%23LeJ&src=hash). And what happened?
> N.O.T.H.I.N.G

[Haider Changezi](https://twitter.com/Aushpaz), a Hazara Twitterati, suggested
on the same day as the market bombing that Pakistani Twitter users unite
against the violence under the hashtag
[#ActionAgainstLeJ](https://twitter.com/search/%23ActionAgainstLeJ):

> @Aushpaz: Dear [#Pakistan](https://twitter.com/search/%23Pakistan) – can we
> for once agree on
> [#ActionAgainstLeJ](https://twitter.com/search/%23ActionAgainstLeJ) – Pls RT
> if you agree with the hashtag so [#PPP](https://twitter.com/search/%23PPP)
> gov knows consensus is there!

Following the attack on Hazara Shias in early January, thousands of Pakistani
protesters attended a four-day vigil,
[demanding](http://dawn.com/2013/01/13/rallies-against-target-killings-in-
quetta/) an “operation cleanup in
[Balochistan](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balochistan,_Pakistan) against
serial killings of Hazara people.” They also called for the removal of
provincial government officials and a handover of the city to the army.
Although the army has not yet been called in, a [state of emergency was
declared](http://tribune.com.pk/story/493704/balochistan-emergency-governors-
rule-imposed/) in the province.

Imran Ali of the BBC [noted](http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21485731)
that the government has yet to arrest those responsible for the bombings:

> After the last bomb attack in Quetta, and the ensuing protests by the Hazara
> community, the Pakistan government sacked Baluchistan's chief minister,
> Nawab Aslam Raisani, but has yet to arrest the culprits behind the attack.
> This came as no surprise to the Hazara community, who have yet to see the
> Pakistan government take action against the Sunni extremist group Lashkar-e-
> Jhangvi.

[Yousuf Nazar](https://twitter.com/YousufNazar), a Pakistani author, [wrote
](https://twitter.com/YousufNazar/status/302814162172649473)that joint action
by security forces would be the only way to put an end to the violence:

> [@YousufNazar](https://twitter.com/YousufNazar/status/302814162172649473): A
> joint army/commando/police operation against TTP/LeJ is the only solution.
> They don't even spare women & children; U can't talk to animals

[Aziz Ali](https://twitter.com/azizhazara), a Hazara Twitter user,
[asked](https://twitter.com/azizhazara/status/302877535354617856) why the
government hasn't moved against the authors of the killings:

> [@azizhazara](https://twitter.com/azizhazara/status/302877535354617856): Why
> no one come forward from government and announce targetted action [against]
> the killer and murderer.
> [#ActionAgainstLeJ](https://twitter.com/search?q=%23ActionAgainstLeJ&src=hash)[
> ~~  
> ~~](https://twitter.com/search?q=%23WeAreAllHazara&src=hash)

